Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=447327" target="_blank">a2l</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            All I can say is Mr Iyer's article is completely misleading. Here are my reasons for it. <br/>
His first argument is how the tax rates are high and how its going to affect the poors and how the rates should be capped at 18%. My take is, its really a frivolous expectation to mention rates in the constitutional amendment. The tax rates are supposed to be dynamic to ensure they could be changed based upon economic reality of the day. The bill empowers the committee of states to change the rates with 2/3 majority at any point in time. He really can't expect the government to fix rates in the constitutional amendment so that every time we need a change to the rate a constitutional amendment is required. Thats simply ludicrous.<br/>
His second argument is about 1% surcharge on petroleum products distorts the free market. Notwithstanding the fact that subsidies instituted by congress governments actually distorted the market for last 60 years. In reality,<br/>
the states want 1% petrol surcharge because a major portion of the state revenue comes from charging petroleum products and they don't want to let that go till the GST stabilises and brings in equivalent amount of revenue. Fear of revenue loss was the main reason why most of the states were opposing congress version of GST. Mr. Jaitley managed to build consensus by putting this in. It seems the Congress cleverly wants to dismantle the consensus by insisting for this change.<br/><br/>
Then he raises the bogey of of 27% indirect tax on top of direct tax being at 33%.I find this really a stretched argument. Only 4% of Indians pay direct tax and India has around 30-50% poor people so thats out of the window. Besides, 33% is the tax slab for the people above 10 lakh income. In which world they are considered to be poor? In reality effective tax rate after deducting the deduction even on rich indians is 22%. If Mr. Iyer is paying the taxes at 33% he needs to get a better CA.<br/><br/>
Finally, what he is not mentioning is for many of the products we pay around 30% (if you consider both central and state) of sales tax on the final price that is going to come down to 27%. I guess reducing prices is never going to be part of congresses agenda whether they are in power or opposition. I personally find it appalling that major tax reform that unifies india into a single market is being stalled for petty politics.
