Selective exemption of GST on certain items does not make for a uniform tax code for indirect taxes. Take for instance the exemption of Liquor/ Tobacco:<br/>
Indian alcohol (for human consumption) market is approx 35 Bln US$. 12 Bln comes from the Organised sector and 22 .5 Bln is owned by the 'country liquor' segment. At 18% GST, that would be approx 6 Bln in tax revenue to the government while @27% (as proposed by Jaitley) that would mean 9 Bln in revenue - that's more than our total arms purchase from the USA in the last 10 years (which includes 12 C-130J Hercules, 8 P8I maritime reconnaisance aircrafts and 10 C17 globemaster III gigantic airlift aircrafts) Add 1 Bln to the 9Bln lost GST and we could buy all of the above military equipments once more and ALSO buy 22 Apache attack helicopters and 15 Chinooks.<br/><br/>
Now about tobacco - indian market size for tobacco is 245 Bln USD and growing at 11% CAGR. That would be approx 44 Bln in GST from Cigarettes, Bidis and Gutkas. <br/>
Considering the fact that alcohol and tobacco does not exactly contribute to social development, it is probably worthwhile for the government to review the feedback provided by the Congress and others........FOR THE GOOD OF ALL OF US, INDIANS. Let our leaders keep aside the interests of the financial contributors to their election fund and instead look after the interests of every indian when they draft and table legislations!
